  "prompt": "How does snow go through sublimation?",
  "response": "Sublimation is a process where a solid changes directly into a gas without first becoming a liquid. In the case of snow, sublimation occurs when snow or ice transitions from a solid state to water vapor without melting into liquid water first. This typically happens under specific conditions:\n\n1. Low humidity\n2. Low air pressure\n3. Relatively warm and dry air\n4. Direct sunlight or wind exposure\n\nDuring sublimation, snow crystals lose mass and gradually disappear by converting directly into water vapor. This process is more common in dry, cold environments with low humidity, such as high-altitude mountain regions or arctic areas.\n\nFactors that accelerate sublimation include:\n- Strong winds\n- High temperatures\n- Low atmospheric moisture\n- Direct sunlight\n- Low air pressure\n\nThe rate of sublimation depends on the surrounding environmental conditions and can vary significantly based on temperature, humidity, and air movement.",
